## 4. STORAGE & LATER ACCESS
- **Where**: Filter bad records into a separate DataFrame and save them to a "Reject" folder (e.g., `s3://bucket/bad_records/`).
- **Access**: Later, a Data Analyst or Engineer reads that "Reject" folder to fix the source data or investigate the root cause.

## CODE EXAMPLE
```python
schema = StructType([
    StructField("id", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("name", StringType(), True),
    StructField("_bad_data", StringType(), True) # Special column
])

df = spark.read.format("json") \
    .option("columnNameOfCorruptRecord", "_bad_data") \
    .schema(schema) \
    .load("path")

# Separate and Store
bad_df = df.filter(df._bad_data.isNotNull())
bad_df.write.parquet("s3://rejected_data/date=2026-04-22/")
